This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

Assessing¶

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset is made up of 16 columns and a total of 183412 rows (inclusive of rows with missing values). Majority of the variables (9) are numeric (float and imteger) in nature, while the remaining (5) variables are categorical in nature. It is important to note that some of the column datatypes are invalid.

Norminal variables include:

  • member_gender (male, female, other)
  • user_type (customer, subscriber)
  • bike_share_for_all_trip (yes, no)

The most notable issues at first glance are:

Quality Issues¶

#1: Missing values in 6 columns: start_station_id, end_station_id, start_station_name, end_station_name, member_birth_year and member_gender.

#2: Wrong data types in these columns: start_time, end_time, start_station_id, end_station_id, bike_id, member_birth_year.

#3: Invalid entries in member_birth_year column, i.e the oldest registered member born in 1878.

Note: There is no noticeable data tidiness issue in this dataset.

Let's clean the identified issues.

Cleaning¶

Issue 1: Missing values in 6 columns¶

Define¶

Note: Since there is no way of acquiring the missing values, and that the number of rows is significantly low, let's leave the columns as they are.

However,

IMPORTANT : We will drop all rows without a start_station_id and end_station_id. This way, we are left only with data of members who were recorded to have started and ended at given stations.

Code¶

In [7]:
# dropping rows without start station id
bike_data.drop(bike_data[bike_data['start_station_id'].isnull()].index,inplace=True)

# droppin rows without end station id
bike_data.drop(bike_data[bike_data['end_station_id'].isnull()].index,inplace=True)

Issue 2: Wrong data types¶

Define¶

  • Convert start_time and end_time from object to datetime datatype using pandas' .astype.

  • Convert start_station_id and end_station_id from float to string (object) datatype.

  • Convert bike_id from int to string datatype. We do not intend to do calculations with it.

  • For the member_birth_year column, we first replace all NaN values with zero(0) using .fillna() then use .astype method to convert the datatype from float to int.

Code¶

In [10]:
# converting start_time and end_time to datetime.
bike_data['start_time'] = bike_data['start_time'].astype('datetime64')
bike_data['end_time'] = bike_data['end_time'].astype('datetime64')


# converting start_station_id and end_station_id from float to string.
bike_data['start_station_id'] = bike_data['start_station_id'].astype(str).replace('nan', np.nan)
bike_data['end_station_id'] = bike_data['end_station_id'].astype(str).replace('nan', np.nan)


# converting bike_id from int to string.
bike_data['bike_id'] = bike_data['bike_id'].astype(str)
In [11]:
# replacing NaN with zero then converting member_birth_year from float to int.

bike_data['member_birth_year'] = bike_data['member_birth_year'].replace(np.nan, 0)
In [12]:
bike_data['member_birth_year'] = bike_data['member_birth_year'].astype(int).replace(0, np.nan)

Issue #3: Invalid entries in member_birth_year column¶

Note: Some records in the dataset show people born in 1930 (older than 90 years) or earlier (others upto 144 years - born in 1878). It is not always common for elderly people to ride bicycles.

IMPORTANT: Therefore, for purposes of the analysis, we will work with data of people born between 1941 (currently aged 80) and the present year (2022).

In [20]:
# function that takes in variable(column) and title
def pie_chart(col, ttl):
    
    plt.pie(col, labels=col.index, startangle = 90, autopct = '%0.0f%%', counterclock = False)
    plt.title(ttl)
    plt.axis('square');

Q 4: How is age distributed across members¶

Note: We will be plotting histograms in this project, let's define a function to use across the project to avoid code repetition.

In [27]:
# Defining function for histograms

def hist_plot(d_set, x_ax, binz, x_lab, y_lab, ttl):
    
    plt.hist(data = d_set, x = x_ax, bins = binz)
    plt.xlabel(x_lab)
    plt.ylabel(y_lab)
    plt.title(ttl);

Let's plot two histograms (using matplotlib and seaborn) side by side to see the age distribution representation.

In [28]:
# resizing the chart to have two plots side-by-side
plt.figure(figsize = [16, 5])

# histogram on the left -- using matplotlib
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)

          'Frequency', 'Distribution of Age across users')

# histogram on the right -- using seaborn
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)

Observation¶

Note: The bin sizes for the two plot are not equal. The first plot has larger bins while the second has smaller bins.

Let's equate the bin sizes and see how they compare

In [29]:
# resizing the chart to have two plots side-by-side
plt.figure(figsize = [16, 5])

# histogram on the left -- using matplotlib
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
bins = np.arange(0, bike_data['age'].max()+3, 3)
hist_plot(bike_data, 'age', bins, 'Age',
          'Frequency', 'Distribution of Age across users')
plt.xlim((15, 85))


# histogram on the right -- using seaborn
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
bin_edges = np.arange(0, bike_data['age'].max()+3, 3)
sb.distplot(bike_data['age'], bins = bin_edges,
            hist_kws = {'alpha' : 0.5}).set(title='Distribution of Age across users');

Observation¶

  • Both distributions are unimodal
  • Both are skewed to the right
  • It appears that most members are aged between 25 and 45 years.

Observation¶

  • The distribution is unimodal and skewed to the right.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distributions showed that majority of users (89%) of the system are subscribed while only 11% of the users are not. For both subscribers and non-subscribers, males account for the highest percentages followed by females and lastly others. Those identifying as others could be members of the "LGBTQ" community. We could conclude that men are fond of bike riding than the other genders.

The distributions on Age showed that the majority of riders are between ages 25 and 45, while the vast minority is the elderly. This means that youth and middle aged people are more into bike riding than the elderly.

Distributions on the duration showed a majority of the users averaging about 726 seconds (10 to 15 minutes) rides. There are lesser people riding for longer durations.

Transformations: To show age distributions, I had to create a column (age) from the differnce of current year of working this project (2022) and each members' year of birth.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

For age distribution, I equated the bin sizes for uniformity since i was using both matplotlib and seaborn in plotting.

For duration, the initial distribution was just one bar with an almost-unclear outlier , I changed the bin size to 100 so as to get a detailed distribution of the data. I also reduced the axis limits to 5000 for clarity of peaks.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Based on the analysis, it is evident that biking is male dominated as we have a large number of male riders both in customer and subscriber categories.

Most riders are either youth or middle-aged in both user categories and also they avergae higher riding durations as expected. It is however interesting that there are elderly people who can average close to 10 minutes of riding.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

When looking at riding duration across user types (customer and subcriber), I noticed that customers(non-members) average higher durations than subscribers. This is counter-intuitive as one would expect subscribers (who are definitely bike lovers) to average higher durations than regular customers.

However, this could either be because, since most customers are not (presumably) regular riders, every time they decide to ride, they do it for longer to quench their longing and excitement, or, averages for subscribers are lower because of their consideraley large number than customers, which affects computations.

Another feature of interest was how top 9 most preffered start stations were also among the most preffered stations to finish at.

Conclusion¶

IMPORTANT: The concluions reached from answering the questions asked are based on analysis done for data of bike users *born between 1941 (currently aged 80) and the present year (2022) and not based on the entire dataset.

We can conclude that, Subscribers form the majority of users, accounting for 89% of all bike users while Customers make up for the remaining 11% of bike users. It is also evident that biking is male dominated since we have the largest number of users being Male in both Customer and Subscriber categories.

Most riders are either youth or middle-aged (ages of 25-45 years) in both user categories. Generally, Subscribers record slightly higher average ages than Customers across the three gender categories. It's important to note that the average ages across the two user types are for middle-aged people.

Majority of the users average about 726 seconds (10 to 15 minutes) rides. Customers average higher durations than subscribers in all three gender categories. As age advances from 45 onwards, the riding duration decreases.
